# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buell-military-commission
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:buell-military-commission/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was born into poverty and never attended school.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was apprenticed as a tailor and worked in several frontier towns before settling in Greeneville, Tennessee, serving as an alderman and mayor before being elected to the Tennessee House of Representatives in 1835.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] After briefly serving in the Tennessee Senate, Johnson was elected to the U.S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] House of Representatives in 1843, where he served five two-year terms.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was the governor of Tennessee for four years, and was elected by the legislature to the U.S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] During his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill, which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In February 1861, Slave states in the Southern U.S., including Tennessee, seceded to form the Confederate States of America, but Johnson remained firmly with the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was the only senator from a Confederate state who did not promptly resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as Military Governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was a logical choice as Lincoln's running mate in 1864 because Lincoln wanted to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Following their victory, Johnson became vice president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson implemented his own form of Presidential Reconstruction, a series of proclamations directing the seceded states to hold conventions and elections to reform their civil governments.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Southern states returned many of their old leaders and passed Black Codes to deprive the freedmen of many civil liberties, but Congressional Republicans refused to seat legislators from those states and advanced legislation to overrule the Southern actions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson vetoed their bills, and Congressional Republicans overrode him, setting a pattern for the remainder of his presidency.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson opposed the Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Constitution, which gave citizenship to former slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1866, he went on an unprecedented national tour promoting his executive policies, seeking to break Republican opposition.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] As the conflict grew between the branches of government, Congress passed the Tenure of Office Act (1867), restricting Johnson's ability to fire Cabinet officials.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He persisted in trying to dismiss the Secretary of War, Edwin Stanton, but ended up being impeached by the House of Representatives and narrowly avoided conviction in the Senate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He did not win the 1868 Democratic presidential nomination and left office the following year.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson returned to Tennessee after his presidency and gained some vindication when he was elected to the Senate in 1875, making him the only former president to serve in the Senate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's strong opposition to federally guaranteed rights for African Americans is widely criticized, and historians have consistently ranked him as one of the worst U.S. presidents.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew Johnson was born in Raleigh, North Carolina, on December 29, 1808, to Jacob Johnson and Mary ("Polly") McDonough, a laundress.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was of English, Scots-Irish, and Scottish ancestry.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He had a brother, William, four years his senior, and an older sister Elizabeth, who died in childhood.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's birth in a two-room shack was a political asset in the mid-19th century, and he frequently reminded voters of his humble origins.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Jacob Johnson was a poor man, as had been his father, William Johnson, but he became town constable of Raleigh before marrying and starting a family.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Jacob Johnson had been a porter for the State Bank of North Carolina, appointed by William Polk, a relative of President James K.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Both Jacob and Mary were illiterate, and had worked as tavern servants, while Johnson never attended school and grew up in poverty.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Jacob died of an apparent heart attack while ringing the town bell, shortly after rescuing three drowning men, when his son Andrew was three.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Polly Johnson worked as a washerwoman and became the sole support of her family.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Her occupation was then looked down on, as it often took her into other homes unaccompanied.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Since Andrew did not resemble either of his siblings, there are rumors that he may have been fathered by another man.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Polly Johnson eventually remarried to a man named Turner Doughtry, who was as poor as she was.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's mother apprenticed her son William to a tailor, James Selby.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew also became an apprentice in Selby's shop at age ten and was legally bound to serve until his 21st birthday.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson lived with his mother for part of his service, and one of Selby's employees taught him rudimentary literacy skills.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] His education was augmented by citizens who would come to Selby's shop to read to the tailors as they worked.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Even before he became an apprentice, Johnson came to listen.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The readings instilled in him a lifelong love of learning, and his biographer Annette Gordon-Reed suggests that Johnson, later a gifted public speaker, learned the art as he threaded needles and cut cloth.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was unhappy at James Selby's, and after about five years, he and his brother ran away.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Selby responded by placing a reward for their return: "Ten Dollars Reward.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Fearing he would be arrested and returned to Raleigh, Johnson moved to Laurens, South Carolina.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He found work quickly, met his first love, Mary Wood, and made her a quilt as a gift.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] However, she rejected his marriage proposal.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He returned to Raleigh, hoping to buy out his apprenticeship, but could not come to terms with Selby.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Unable to stay in Raleigh, where he risked being apprehended for abandoning Selby, he decided to move west.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson left North Carolina for Tennessee, traveling mostly on foot.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] After a brief period in Knoxville, he moved to Mooresville, Alabama.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He then worked as a tailor in Columbia, Tennessee, but was called back to Raleigh by his mother and stepfather, who saw limited opportunities there and who wished to emigrate west.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson and his party traveled through the Blue Ridge Mountains to Greeneville, Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew Johnson fell in love with the town at first sight, and when he became prosperous purchased the land where he had first camped and planted a tree in commemoration.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In Greeneville, Johnson established a successful tailoring business in the front of his home.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1827, at the age of 18, he married 16-year-old Eliza McCardle, the daughter of a local shoemaker.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The pair were married by Justice of the Peace Mordecai Lincoln, first cousin of Thomas Lincoln, whose son would become president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Johnsons were married for almost 50 years and had five children: Martha (1828), Charles (1830), Mary (1832), Robert (1834), and Andrew Jr.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Though she had tuberculosis, Eliza supported her husband's endeavors.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] She taught him mathematics skills and tutored him to improve his writing.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Shy and retiring by nature, Eliza Johnson usually remained in Greeneville during Johnson's political rise.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] She was not often seen during her husband's presidency; their daughter Martha usually served as official hostess.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's tailoring business prospered during the early years of the marriage, enabling him to hire help and giving him the funds to invest profitably in real estate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He later boasted of his talents as a tailor, "my work never ripped or gave way".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Books about famous orators aroused his interest in political dialogue, and he had private debates on the issues of the day with customers who held opposing views.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He also took part in debates at Greeneville College.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1843, Johnson purchased his first slave, Dolly, who was 14 years old at the time.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Dolly had three children—Liz, Florence and William.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Soon after his purchase of Dolly, he purchased Dolly's half-brother Sam.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Sam Johnson and his wife Margaret had nine children.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Sam became a commissioner of the Freedmen's Bureau and was known for being a proud man who negotiated the nature of his work with the Johnson family.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Notably, he received some monetary compensation for his labors and negotiated with Andrew Johnson to receive a tract of land which Johnson gave him for free in 1867.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1857, Johnson purchased Henry, who was 13 at the time and would later accompany the Johnson family to the White House.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Ultimately, Johnson owned at least ten slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew Johnson freed his slaves on August 8, 1863; they remained with him as paid servants.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] A year later, Johnson, as military governor of Tennessee, proclaimed the freedom of Tennessee's slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Sam and Margaret, Johnson's former slaves, lived in his tailor shop while he was president, without rent.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] As a sign of appreciation for proclaiming freedom, Andrew Johnson was given a watch by newly emancipated people in Tennessee inscribed with "for his Untiring Energy in the Cause of Freedom".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson helped organize a Mechanics' (Working Men's) ticket in the 1829 Greeneville municipal election.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was elected town alderman, along with his friends Blackston McDannel and Mordecai Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Following Nat Turner's Rebellion in 1831, a state convention was called to pass a new constitution, including provisions to disenfranchise free people of color.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The convention also wanted to reform real estate tax rates, and provide ways of funding improvements to Tennessee's infrastructure.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The constitution was submitted for a public vote, and Johnson spoke widely for its adoption; the successful campaign provided him with statewide exposure.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] On January 4, 1834, his fellow aldermen elected him mayor of Greeneville.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1835, Johnson made a bid for election to the "floater" (open) seat which Greene County shared with neighboring Washington County in the Tennessee House of Representatives.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Trefousse, Johnson "demolished" the opposition in debate and won the election with a near-two-to-one margin.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] During his Greeneville days, Johnson joined the Tennessee Militia as a member of the 90th Regiment.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He attained the rank of colonel, though while an enrolled member, Johnson was fined for an unknown offense.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Afterwards, he was often addressed or referred to by his rank.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In his first term in the legislature, which met in the state capital of Nashville, Johnson did not consistently vote with either the Democratic or the newly formed Whig Party, though he revered President Andrew Jackson, a Democrat and fellow Tennessean.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The major parties were still determining their core values and policy proposals, with the party system in a state of flux.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] After Brookins Campbell and the Whigs defeated Johnson for reelection in 1837, Johnson would not lose another race for thirty years.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1839, he sought to regain his seat, initially as a Whig, but when another candidate sought the Whig nomination, he ran as a Democrat and was elected.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] From that time he supported the Democratic party and built a powerful political machine in Greene County.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson became a strong advocate for the Democratic Party.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was noted for his oratory in an era when public speaking both informed and entertained the public; people flocked to hear him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1840, Johnson was selected as a presidential elector for Tennessee, giving him more statewide publicity.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Democratic President Martin Van Buren was defeated by former Ohio senator William Henry Harrison, Johnson was instrumental in keeping Greene County in the Democratic column.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was elected to the Tennessee Senate in 1841, where he served a two-year term.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He had achieved financial success in his tailoring business, but sold it to concentrate on politics.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He had also acquired additional real estate, including a larger home and a farm (where his mother and stepfather took residence), and among his assets numbered eight or nine slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Having served in both houses of the state legislature, Johnson saw election to Congress as the next step in his political career.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He engaged in a number of political maneuvers to gain Democratic support, including the displacement of the Whig postmaster in Greeneville, and defeated Jonesborough lawyer John A.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In Washington, he joined a new Democratic majority in the House of Representatives.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson advocated for the interests of the poor, maintained an anti-abolitionist stance, argued for only limited spending by the government and opposed protective tariffs.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] With Eliza remaining in Greeneville, Congressman Johnson shunned social functions in favor of study in the Library of Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although a fellow Tennessee Democrat, James K.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Polk, was elected president in 1844, and Johnson had campaigned for him, the two men had difficult relations, and President Polk refused some of his patronage suggestions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson believed, as did many Southern Democrats, that the Constitution protected private property, including slaves, and thus prohibited the federal and state governments from abolishing slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He won a second term in 1845 against William G.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Brownlow, presenting himself as the defender of the poor against the aristocracy.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In his second term, Johnson supported the Polk administration's decision to fight the Mexican War, seen by some Northerners as an attempt to gain territory to expand slavery westward, and opposed the Wilmot Proviso, a proposal to ban slavery in any territory gained from Mexico.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He introduced for the first time his Homestead Bill, to grant 160 acres (65 ha) to people willing to settle the land and gain title to it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] This issue was especially important to Johnson because of his own humble beginnings.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In the presidential election of 1848, the Democrats split over the slavery issue, and abolitionists formed the Free Soil Party, with former president Van Buren as their nominee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson supported the Democratic candidate, former Michigan senator Lewis Cass.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] With the party split, Whig nominee General Zachary Taylor was easily victorious, and carried Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, due to national interest in new railroad construction and in response to the need for better transportation in his own district, also supported government assistance for the East Tennessee and Virginia Railroad.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] During his campaign for a fourth term, Johnson concentrated on three issues: slavery, homesteads and judicial elections.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Taylor, in August 1849, with a greater margin of victory than in previous campaigns.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] When the House convened in December, the party division caused by the Free Soil Party precluded the formation of the majority needed to elect a Speaker.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson proposed adoption of a rule allowing election of a Speaker by a plurality; some weeks later others took up a similar proposal, and Democrat Howell Cobb was elected.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Once the Speaker election had concluded and Congress was ready to conduct legislative business, the issue of slavery took center stage.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Northerners sought to admit California, a free state, to the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Kentucky's Henry Clay introduced in the Senate a series of resolutions, the Compromise of 1850, to admit California and pass legislation sought by each side.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson voted for all the provisions except for the abolition of the slave trade in the nation's capital.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He pressed resolutions for constitutional amendments to provide for popular election of senators (then elected by state legislatures) and of the president (chosen by the Electoral College), and limiting the tenure of federal judges to 12 years.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] A group of Democrats nominated Landon Carter Haynes to oppose Johnson as he sought a fifth term; the Whigs were so pleased with the internecine battle among the Democrats in the general election that they did not nominate a candidate of their own.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The campaign included fierce debates: Johnson's main issue was the passage of the Homestead Bill; Haynes contended it would facilitate abolition.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson won the election by more than 1,600 votes.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Though he was not enamored of the party's presidential nominee in 1852, former New Hampshire senator Franklin Pierce, Johnson campaigned for him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Pierce was elected, but he failed to carry Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1852, Johnson managed to get the House to pass his Homestead Bill, but it failed in the Senate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Whigs had gained control of the Tennessee legislature, and, under the leadership of Gustavus Henry, redrew the boundaries of Johnson's First District to make it a safe seat for their party.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] During this period, Johnson became a Freemason, initiated into Greenville Lodge No.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] If Johnson considered retiring from politics upon deciding not to seek reelection, he soon changed his mind.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] His political friends began to maneuver to get him the nomination for governor.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Democratic convention unanimously named him, though some party members were not happy at his selection.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Whigs had won the past two gubernatorial elections, and still controlled the legislature.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] That party nominated Henry, making the "Henry-mandering" of the First District an immediate issue.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The two men debated in county seats the length of Tennessee before the meetings were called off two weeks before the August 1853 election due to illness in Henry's family.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson won the election by 63,413 votes to 61,163; some votes for him were cast in return for his promise to support Whig Nathaniel Taylor for his old seat in Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Tennessee's governor had little power: Johnson could propose legislation but not veto it, and most appointments were made by the Whig-controlled legislature.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Nevertheless, the office was a "bully pulpit" that allowed him to publicize himself and his political views.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He succeeded in getting the appointments he wanted in return for his endorsement of John Bell, a Whig, for one of the state's U.S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In his first biennial speech, Johnson urged simplification of the state judicial system, abolition of the Bank of Tennessee, and establishment of an agency to provide uniformity in weights and measures; the last was passed.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was critical of the Tennessee common school system and suggested funding be increased via taxes, either statewide or county by county—a mixture of the two was passed.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Reforms carried out during Johnson's time as governor included the foundation of the State's public library (making books available to all) and its first public school system, and the initiation of regular state fairs to benefit craftsmen and farmers.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although the Whig Party was on its final decline nationally, it remained strong in Tennessee, and the outlook for Democrats there in 1855 was poor.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Feeling that reelection as governor was necessary to give him a chance at the higher offices he sought, Johnson agreed to make the run.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] A series of more than a dozen vitriolic debates ensued.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The issues in the campaign were slavery, the prohibition of alcohol, and the nativist positions of the Know Nothing Party.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson favored the first, but opposed the others.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Gentry was more equivocal on the alcohol question, and had gained the support of the Know Nothings, a group Johnson portrayed as a secret society.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was unexpectedly victorious, albeit with a narrower margin than in 1853.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] When the presidential election of 1856 approached, Johnson hoped to be nominated; some Tennessee county conventions designated him a "favorite son".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] His position that the best interests of the Union were served by slavery in some areas made him a practical compromise candidate for president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He was never a major contender; the nomination fell to former Pennsylvania senator James Buchanan.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Though he was not impressed by either, Johnson campaigned for Buchanan and his running mate, John C.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson decided not to seek a third term as governor, with an eye towards election to the U.S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1857, while returning from Washington, his train derailed, causing serious damage to his right arm.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] This injury would trouble him in the years to come.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The victors in the 1857 state legislative campaign would, once they convened in October, elect a United States Senator.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Campbell wrote to his uncle, "The great anxiety of the Whigs is to elect a majority in the legislature so as to defeat Andrew Johnson for senator.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Should the Democrats have the majority, he will certainly be their choice, and there is no man living to whom the Americans and Whigs have as much antipathy as Johnson." The governor spoke widely in the campaign, and his party won the gubernatorial race and control of the legislature.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's final address as governor gave him the chance to influence his electors, and he made proposals popular among Democrats.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Two days later the legislature elected him to the Senate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The opposition was appalled, with the Richmond *Whig* newspaper referring to him as "the vilest radical and most unscrupulous demagogue in the Union".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson gained high office due to his proven record as a man popular among the small farmers and self-employed tradesmen who made up much of Tennessee's electorate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He called them the "plebeians"; he was less popular among the planters and lawyers who led the state Democratic Party, but none could match him as a vote-getter.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Mostly denied the party's machinery, he relied on a network of friends, advisers, and contacts.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] One friend, Hugh Douglas, stated in a letter to him, "you have been in the way of our would be great men for a long time.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] At heart many of us never wanted you to be Governor only none of the rest of us Could have been elected at the time and we only wanted to use you.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The new senator took his seat when Congress convened in December 1857 (the term of his predecessor, James C.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He came to Washington as usual without his wife and family; Eliza would visit Washington only once during Johnson's first time as senator, in 1860.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson immediately set about introducing the Homestead Bill in the Senate, but as most senators who supported it were Northern (many associated with the newly founded Republican Party), the matter became caught up in suspicions over the slavery issue.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Southern senators felt that those who took advantage of the provisions of the Homestead Bill were more likely to be Northern non-slaveholders.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The issue of slavery had been complicated by the Supreme Court's ruling earlier in the year in *Dred Scott v.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Sandford* that slavery could not be prohibited in the territories.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, a slaveholding senator from a Southern state, made a major speech in the Senate the following May in an attempt to convince his colleagues that the Homestead Bill and slavery were not incompatible.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Nevertheless, Southern opposition was key to defeating the legislation, 30–22.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1859, it failed on a procedural vote when Vice President Breckinridge broke a tie against the bill, and in 1860, a watered-down version passed both houses, only to be vetoed by Buchanan at the urging of Southerners.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson continued his opposition to spending, chairing a committee to control it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He argued against funding to build infrastructure in Washington, D.C., stating that it was unfair to expect state citizens to pay for the city's streets, even if it was the seat of government.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He opposed spending money for troops to put down the revolt by the Mormons in Utah Territory, arguing for temporary volunteers as the United States should not have a standing army.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In October 1859, abolitionist John Brown and sympathizers raided the federal arsenal at Harpers Ferry, Virginia (today West Virginia).
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Tensions in Washington between pro- and anti-slavery forces increased greatly.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson gave a major speech in the Senate in December, decrying Northerners who would endanger the Union by seeking to outlaw slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Tennessee senator stated that "all men are created equal" from the Declaration of Independence did not apply to African Americans, since the Constitution of Illinois contained that phrase—and that document barred voting by African Americans.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, by this time, was a wealthy man who owned 14 slaves.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson hoped that he would be a compromise candidate for the presidential nomination as the Democratic Party tore itself apart over the slavery question.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Busy with the Homestead Bill during the 1860 Democratic National Convention in Charleston, South Carolina, he sent two of his sons and his chief political adviser to represent his interests in the backroom deal-making.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The convention deadlocked, with no candidate able to gain the required two-thirds vote, but the sides were too far apart to consider Johnson as a compromise.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The party split, with Northerners backing Illinois Senator Stephen Douglas while Southerners, including Johnson, supported Vice President Breckinridge for president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] With former Tennessee senator John Bell running a fourth-party candidacy and further dividing the vote, the Republican Party elected its first president, former Illinois representative Abraham Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The election of Lincoln, known to be against the spread of slavery, was unacceptable to many in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although secession from the Union had not been an issue in the campaign, talk of it began in the Southern states.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson took to the Senate floor after the election, giving a speech well received in the North, "I will not give up this government ...
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Gordon-Reed points out that while Johnson's belief in an indissoluble Union was sincere, he had alienated Southern leaders, including Davis, who would soon be the president of the Confederate States of America, formed by the seceding states.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] If the Tennessean had backed the Confederacy, he would have had small influence in its government.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson returned home when his state took up the issue of secession.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Harris, and the legislature organized a referendum on whether to have a constitutional convention to authorize secession; when that failed, they put the question of leaving the Union to a popular vote.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Despite threats on Johnson's life, and actual assaults, he campaigned against both questions, sometimes speaking with a gun on the lectern before him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Johnson's eastern region of Tennessee was largely against secession, the second referendum passed, and in June 1861, Tennessee joined the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Believing he would be killed if he stayed, Johnson fled through the Cumberland Gap, where his party was in fact shot at.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He left his wife and family in Greeneville.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] As the only member from a seceded state to remain in the Senate and the most prominent Southern Unionist, Johnson had Lincoln's ear in the early months of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] With most of Tennessee in Confederate hands, Johnson spent congressional recesses in Kentucky and Ohio, trying in vain to convince any Union commander who would listen to conduct an operation into East Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's first tenure in the Senate came to a conclusion in March 1862 when Lincoln appointed him military governor of Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Much of the central and western portions of that seceded state had been recovered.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although some argued that civil government should simply resume once the Confederates were defeated in an area, Lincoln chose to use his power as commander in chief to appoint military governors over Union-controlled Southern regions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Senate quickly confirmed Johnson's nomination along with the rank of brigadier general.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In response, the Confederates confiscated his land and his slaves, and turned his home into a military hospital.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Later in 1862, after his departure from the Senate and in the absence of most Southern legislators, the Homestead Bill was finally enacted.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Along with legislation for land-grant colleges and for the transcontinental railroad, the Homestead Bill has been credited with opening the Western United States to settlement.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] As military governor, Johnson sought to eliminate rebel influence in the state.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He demanded loyalty oaths from public officials, and shut down all newspapers owned by Confederate sympathizers.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Much of eastern Tennessee remained in Confederate hands, and the ebb and flow of war during 1862 sometimes brought Confederate control again close to Nashville.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] However, the Confederates allowed his wife and family to pass through the lines to join him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson undertook the defense of Nashville as well as he could, though the city was continually harassed by cavalry raids led by General Nathan Bedford Forrest.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Relief from Union regulars did not come until General William S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Rosecrans defeated the Confederates at Murfreesboro in early 1863.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Much of eastern Tennessee was captured later that year.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] When Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863, declaring freedom for all slaves in Confederate-held areas, he exempted Tennessee at Johnson's request.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The proclamation increased the debate over what should become of the slaves after the war, as not all Unionists supported abolition.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson finally decided that slavery had to end.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He wrote, "If the institution of slavery ... seeks to overthrow it [the Government], then the Government has a clear right to destroy it".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He reluctantly supported efforts to enlist former slaves into the Union army, feeling that African-Americans should perform menial tasks to release white Americans to do the fighting.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Nevertheless, he oversaw the recruitment of 20,000 black men into the United States Colored Troops.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1860, Lincoln's running mate had been Senator Hannibal Hamlin of Maine.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Hamlin had served competently, was in good health, and was willing to run again, Johnson emerged as running mate for Lincoln's reelection bid in 1864.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln considered several War Democrats for the ticket in 1864, and sent an agent to sound out General Benjamin Butler as a possible running mate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In May 1864, the president dispatched General Daniel Sickles to Nashville on a fact-finding mission.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Sickles denied that he was there either to investigate or interview the military governor, Johnson biographer Hans L.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Trefousse believes that Sickles's trip was connected to Johnson's subsequent nomination for vice president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] According to historian Albert Castel in his account of Johnson's presidency, Lincoln was impressed by Johnson's administration of Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Dickinson, a War Democrat, as Seward would probably have had to yield his place if another New Yorker became vice president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, once he was told by reporters the likely purpose of Sickles' visit, was active on his own behalf, delivering speeches and having his political friends work behind the scenes to boost his candidacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] To sound a theme of unity in 1864, Lincoln ran under the banner of the National Union Party, rather than that of the Republicans.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] At the party's convention in Baltimore in June, Lincoln was easily nominated, although there had been some talk of replacing him with a cabinet officer or one of the more successful generals.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] After the convention backed Lincoln, former Secretary of War Simon Cameron offered a resolution to nominate Hamlin, but it was defeated.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was nominated for vice president by C.M.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Allen of Indiana with an Iowa delegate seconding it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] On the first ballot, Johnson led with 200 votes to 150 for Hamlin and 108 for Dickinson.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] On the second ballot, Kentucky switched its vote for Johnson, beginning a stampede.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was named on the second ballot with 491 votes to Hamlin's 17 and eight for Dickinson; the nomination was made unanimous.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln expressed pleasure at the result, "Andy Johnson, I think, is a good man." When word reached Nashville, a crowd assembled and the military governor obliged with a speech contending his selection as a Southerner meant that the rebel states had not actually left the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Although it was unusual at the time for a national candidate to actively campaign, Johnson gave a number of speeches in Tennessee, Kentucky, Ohio, and Indiana.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He also sought to boost his chances in Tennessee while reestablishing civil government by making the loyalty oath even more restrictive, in that voters would now have to swear that they opposed making a settlement with the Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] The Democratic candidate for president, George McClellan, hoped to avoid additional bloodshed by negotiation, and so the stricter loyalty oath effectively disenfranchised his supporters.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln declined to override Johnson, and their ticket took the state by 25,000 votes.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Congress refused to count Tennessee's electoral votes, but Lincoln and Johnson did not need them, having won in most states that had voted, and easily secured the election.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Now Vice President-elect, Johnson was eager to complete the work of reestablishing civilian government in Tennessee, although the timetable for the election of a new governor did not allow it to take place until after Inauguration Day, March 4.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] He hoped to remain in Nashville to complete his task, but was told by Lincoln's advisers that he could not stay, but would be sworn in with Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In these months, Union troops finished the retaking of eastern Tennessee, including Greeneville.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Just before his departure, the voters of Tennessee ratified a new constitution, which abolished slavery, on February 22, 1865.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] One of Johnson's final acts as military governor was to certify the results.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] On the evening of March 3, Johnson attended a party in his honor at which he drank heavily.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Hung over the following morning at the Capitol, he asked Vice President Hamlin for some whiskey.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Hamlin produced a bottle, and Johnson took two stiff drinks, stating "I need all the strength for the occasion I can have." In the Senate Chamber, Johnson delivered a rambling address as Lincoln, the Congress, and dignitaries looked on.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Almost incoherent at times, he finally meandered to a halt, whereupon Hamlin hastily swore him in as vice president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln, who had watched sadly during the debacle, then went to his own swearing-in outside the Capitol, and delivered his acclaimed Second Inaugural Address.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] In the weeks after the inauguration, Johnson only presided over the Senate briefly, and hid from public ridicule at the Maryland home of a friend, Francis Preston Blair.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] When he did return to Washington, it was with the intent of leaving for Tennessee to reestablish his family in Greeneville.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Instead, he remained after word came that General Ulysses S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p01] Grant had captured the Confederate capital of Richmond, Virginia, presaging the end of the war.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On the afternoon of April 14, 1865, Lincoln and Johnson met for the first time since the inauguration.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Trefousse states that Johnson wanted to "induce Lincoln not to be too lenient with traitors"; Gordon-Reed agrees.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] That night, President Lincoln was shot and mortally wounded at Ford's Theatre by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The shooting of the President was part of a conspiracy to assassinate Lincoln, Johnson, and Seward the same night.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward barely survived his wounds, while Johnson escaped attack as his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, got drunk instead of killing the vice president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Farwell, a fellow boarder at the Kirkwood House, awoke Johnson with news of Lincoln's shooting.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson rushed to the President's deathbed, where he remained a short time, on his return promising, "They shall suffer for this.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] They shall suffer for this." Lincoln died at 7:22 the next morning; Johnson's swearing-in occurred between 10 and 11 am with Chief Justice Salmon P.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Chase presiding in the presence of most of the Cabinet.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's demeanor was described by the newspapers as "solemn and dignified".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Some Cabinet members had last seen Johnson, apparently drunk, at the inauguration.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] At noon, Johnson conducted his first Cabinet meeting in the Treasury Secretary's office, and asked all members to remain in their positions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The events of the assassination resulted in speculation, then and subsequently, concerning Johnson and what the conspirators might have intended for him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In the vain hope of having his life spared after his capture, Atzerodt spoke much about the conspiracy, but did not say anything to indicate that the plotted assassination of Johnson was merely a ruse.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Conspiracy theorists point to the fact that on the day of the assassination, Booth came to the Kirkwood House and left one of his cards with Johnson's private secretary, William A.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The message on it was: "Don't wish to disturb you.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson presided with dignity over Lincoln's funeral ceremonies in Washington, before his predecessor's body was sent home to Springfield, Illinois, for interment.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Shortly after Lincoln's death, Union General William T.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Sherman reported he had, without consulting Washington, reached an armistice agreement with Confederate General Joseph E.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnston for the surrender of Confederate forces in North Carolina in exchange for the existing state government remaining in power, with private property rights (slaves) to be respected.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] This did not even grant freedom to those in slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] This was not acceptable to Johnson or the Cabinet, who sent word for Sherman to secure the surrender without making political deals, which he did.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Further, Johnson placed a $100,000 bounty (equivalent to $2.1 million in 2025) on Confederate President Davis, then a fugitive, which gave Johnson the reputation of a man who would be tough on the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] More controversially, he permitted the execution of Mary Surratt for her part in Lincoln's assassination.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Surratt was executed with three others, including Atzerodt, on July 7, 1865.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Upon taking office, Johnson faced the question of what to do with the former Confederacy.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress considered this too lenient; its own plan, requiring a majority of voters to take the loyalty oath, passed both houses in 1864, but Lincoln pocket vetoed it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson had three goals in Reconstruction.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He sought a speedy restoration of the states, on the grounds that they had never truly left the Union, and thus should again be recognized once loyal citizens formed a government.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] To Johnson, African-American suffrage was a delay and a distraction; it had always been a state responsibility to decide who should vote.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Second, political power in the Southern states should pass from the planter class to his beloved "plebeians".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson feared that the freedmen, many of whom were still economically bound to their former masters, might vote at their direction.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's third priority was election in his own right in 1868, a feat no one who had succeeded a deceased president had managed to accomplish, attempting to secure a Democratic anti-Congressional Reconstruction coalition in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Republicans had formed a number of factions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Radical Republicans sought voting and other civil rights for African Americans.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] They believed that the freedmen could be induced to vote Republican in gratitude for emancipation, and that black votes could keep the Republicans in power and Southern Democrats, including former rebels, out of influence.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] They believed that top Confederates should be punished.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Moderate Republicans sought to keep the Democrats out of power at a national level, and prevent former rebels from resuming power.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] They were not as enthusiastic about the idea of African-American suffrage as their Radical colleagues, either because of their own local political concerns, or because they believed that the freedman would be likely to cast his vote badly.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Northern Democrats favored the unconditional restoration of the Southern states.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] They did not support African-American suffrage, which might threaten Democratic control in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson was initially left to devise a Reconstruction policy without legislative intervention, as Congress was not due to meet again until December 1865.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Radical Republicans told the President that the Southern states were economically in a state of chaos and urged him to use his leverage to insist on rights for freedmen as a condition of restoration to the Union.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] But Johnson, with the support of other officials including Seward, insisted that the franchise was a state, not a federal matter.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's first Reconstruction actions were two proclamations, with the unanimous backing of his Cabinet, on May 29.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] One recognized the Virginia government led by provisional Governor Francis Pierpont.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The second provided amnesty for all ex-rebels except those holding property valued at $20,000 or more; it also appointed a temporary governor for North Carolina and authorized elections.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Neither of these proclamations included provisions regarding black suffrage or freedmen's rights.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The President ordered constitutional conventions in other former rebel states.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] As Southern states began the process of forming governments, Johnson's policies received considerable public support in the North, which he took as unconditional backing for quick reinstatement of the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] While he received such support from the white South, he underestimated the determination of Northerners to ensure that the war had not been fought for nothing.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] It was important, in Northern public opinion, that the South acknowledge its defeat, that slavery be ended, and that the lot of African Americans be improved.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Voting rights were less important at the time—only a handful of Northern states (mostly in New England) gave African-American men the right to vote on the same basis as whites, and in late 1865, Connecticut, Wisconsin, and Minnesota voted down African-American suffrage proposals by large margins.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Northern public opinion tolerated Johnson's inaction on black suffrage as an experiment, to be allowed if it quickened Southern acceptance of defeat.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Instead, white Southerners felt emboldened.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] A number of Southern states passed Black Codes, binding African-American laborers to farms on annual contracts they could not quit, and allowing law enforcement at whim to arrest them for vagrancy and rent out their labor.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Most Southerners elected to Congress were former Confederates, with the most prominent being Georgia Senator-designate and former Confederate vice president Alexander Stephens.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress assembled in early December 1865; Johnson's conciliatory annual message to them was well received.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Nevertheless, Congress refused to seat the Southern legislators and established a committee to recommend appropriate Reconstruction legislation.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Northerners were outraged at the idea of unrepentant Confederate leaders, such as Stephens, rejoining the federal government at a time when emotional wounds from the war remained raw.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] They saw the Black Codes placing African Americans in a position barely above slavery.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Republicans also feared that restoration of the Southern states would return the Democrats to power.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Stewart in his book on Johnson's impeachment, "the violence and poverty that oppressed the South would galvanize the opposition to Johnson".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress was reluctant to confront the President, and initially only sought to fine-tune Johnson's policies towards the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] By late January 1866, he was convinced that winning a showdown with the Radical Republicans was necessary to his political plans – both for the success of Reconstruction and for reelection in 1868.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He would have preferred that the conflict arise over the legislative efforts to enfranchise African Americans in the District of Columbia, a proposal that had been defeated overwhelmingly in an all-white referendum.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] A bill to accomplish this passed the House of Representatives, but to Johnson's disappointment, stalled in the Senate before he could veto it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Illinois Senator Lyman Trumbull, leader of the Moderate Republicans and Chairman of the Judiciary Committee, was anxious to reach an understanding with the President.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He ushered through Congress a bill extending the Freedmen's Bureau beyond its scheduled abolition in 1867, and the first Civil Rights Bill, to grant citizenship to the freedmen.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Trumbull met several times with Johnson and was convinced the President would sign the measures (Johnson rarely contradicted visitors, often fooling those who met with him into thinking he was in accord).
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In fact, the President opposed both bills as infringements on state sovereignty.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Additionally, both of Trumbull's bills were unpopular among white Southerners, whom Johnson hoped to include in his new party.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson vetoed the Freedman's Bureau bill on February 18, 1866, to the delight of white Southerners and the puzzled anger of Republican legislators.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He considered himself vindicated when a move to override his veto failed in the Senate the following day.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson believed that the Radicals would now be isolated and defeated and that the moderate Republicans would form behind him; he did not understand that Moderates also wanted to see African Americans treated fairly.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On February 22, 1866, Washington's Birthday, Johnson gave an impromptu speech to supporters who had marched to the White House and called for an address in honor of the first president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In his hour-long speech, he instead referred to himself over 200 times.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] More damagingly, he also spoke of "men ... still opposed to the Union" to whom he could not extend the hand of friendship he gave to the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When called upon by the crowd to say who they were, Johnson named Pennsylvania Congressman Thaddeus Stevens, Massachusetts Senator Charles Sumner, and abolitionist Wendell Phillips, and accused them of plotting his assassination.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Republicans viewed the address as a declaration of war, while one Democratic ally estimated Johnson's speech cost the party 200,000 votes in the 1866 congressional midterm elections.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Although strongly urged by moderates to sign the Civil Rights Act of 1866, Johnson broke decisively with them by vetoing it on March 27.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In his veto message, he objected to the measure because it conferred citizenship on the freedmen at a time when 11 out of 36 states were unrepresented in the Congress, and that it "discriminated" in favor of African Americans and against whites.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Within three weeks, Congress had overridden his veto, the first time that had been done on a major bill in American history.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The veto, often seen as a key mistake of Johnson's presidency, convinced moderates there was no hope of working with him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Historian Eric Foner, in his volume on Reconstruction, views it as "the most disastrous miscalculation of his political career".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] According to Stewart, the veto was "for many his defining blunder, setting a tone of perpetual confrontation with Congress that prevailed for the rest of his presidency".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress also proposed the Fourteenth Amendment to the states.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Written by Trumbull and others, it was sent for ratification by state legislatures in a process in which the president plays no part, though Johnson opposed it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The amendment was designed to put the key provisions of the Civil Rights Act into the Constitution, but also went further.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The amendment extended citizenship to every person born in the United States (except Indians on reservations), penalized states that did not give the vote to freedmen, and most importantly, created new federal civil rights that could be protected by federal courts.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] It also guaranteed that the federal debt would be paid and forbade repayment of Confederate war debts.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Further, it disqualified many former Confederates from office, although the disability could be removed — by Congress, not the president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Both houses passed the Freedmen's Bureau Act a second time, and again the President vetoed it; this time, the veto was overridden.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] By the summer of 1866, when Congress finally adjourned, Johnson's method of restoring states to the Union by executive fiat, without safeguards for the freedmen, was in deep trouble.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] His home state of Tennessee ratified the Fourteenth Amendment despite the President's opposition.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When Tennessee did so, Congress immediately seated its proposed delegation, embarrassing Johnson.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Efforts to compromise failed, and a political war ensued between the united Republicans on one side, and on the other, Johnson and his Northern and Southern allies in the Democratic Party.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He called a convention of the National Union Party.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Republicans had returned to using their previous identifier; Johnson intended to use the discarded name to unite his supporters and gain election to a full term, in 1868.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The battleground was the election of 1866; Southern states were not allowed to vote.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson campaigned vigorously, undertaking a public speaking tour, known as the "Swing Around the Circle".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The trip, including speeches in Chicago, St.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Louis, Indianapolis, and Columbus, proved politically disastrous, with the President making controversial comparisons between himself and Jesus, and engaging in arguments with hecklers.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] These exchanges were attacked as beneath the dignity of the presidency.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Republicans won by a landslide, increasing their two-thirds majority in Congress, and made plans to control Reconstruction.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson blamed the Democrats for giving only lukewarm support to the National Union movement.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Even with the Republican victory in November 1866, Johnson considered himself in a strong position.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Fourteenth Amendment had not yet been ratified by enough states to go into force, with Tennessee alone among the Southern or border states in voting for it.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] As the amendment required ratification by three-quarters of the states to become part of the Constitution, he believed the deadlock would be broken in his favor, leading to his election in 1868.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Once it reconvened in December 1866, an energized Congress began passing legislation, often over a presidential veto; this included the District of Columbia voting bill.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress admitted Nebraska to the Union over a veto, and the Republicans gained two senators and a state that promptly ratified the amendment.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's veto of a bill for statehood for Colorado Territory was sustained; enough senators agreed that a district with a population of 30,000 was not yet worthy of statehood to win the day.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In January 1867, Congressman Stevens introduced legislation to dissolve the Southern state governments and reconstitute them into five military districts, under martial law.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The states would begin again by holding constitutional conventions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] African Americans could vote for or become delegates; former Confederates could not.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In the legislative process, Congress added to the bill that restoration to the Union would follow the state's ratification of the Fourteenth Amendment, and completion of the process of adding it to the Constitution.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson and the Southerners attempted a compromise, whereby the South would agree to a modified version of the amendment without the disqualification of former Confederates, and for limited black suffrage.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Republicans insisted on the full language of the amendment, and the deal fell through.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Although Johnson could have pocket vetoed the First Reconstruction Act as it was presented to him less than ten days before the end of the Thirty-Ninth Congress, he chose to veto it directly on March 2, 1867; Congress overruled him the same day.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Also on March 2, Congress passed the Tenure of Office Act over the President's veto, in response to statements during the Swing Around the Circle that he planned to fire Cabinet secretaries who did not agree with him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Secretary of War Edwin Stanton was an able and hard-working man, but difficult to deal with.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson both admired and was exasperated by his War Secretary, who, in combination with General of the Army Grant, worked to undermine the president's Southern policy from within his own administration.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson considered firing Stanton, but respected him for his wartime service as secretary.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton, for his part, feared allowing Johnson to appoint his successor and refused to resign, despite his public disagreements with his president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The new Congress met for a few weeks in March 1867, then adjourned, leaving the House Committee on the Judiciary behind, tasked in the first impeachment inquiry against Johnson with reporting back to the full House whether there were grounds for Johnson to be impeached.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] This committee duly met, examined the President's bank accounts, and summoned members of the Cabinet to testify.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When a federal court released former Confederate president Davis on bail on May 13 (he had been captured shortly after the war), the committee investigated whether the President had impeded the prosecution.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] It learned that Johnson was eager to have Davis tried.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] A bipartisan majority of the committee voted down impeachment charges; the committee adjourned on June 3.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Later in June, Johnson and Stanton battled over the question of whether the military officers placed in command of the South could override the civil authorities.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The President had Attorney General Henry Stanbery issue an opinion backing his position that they could not.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson sought to pin down Stanton either as for, and thus endorsing Johnson's position, or against, showing himself to be opposed to his president and the rest of the Cabinet.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton evaded the point in meetings and written communications.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When Congress reconvened in July, it passed a Reconstruction Act against Johnson's position, waited for his veto, overrode it, and went home.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In addition to clarifying the powers of the generals, the legislation also deprived the President of control over the Army in the South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] With Congress in recess until November, Johnson decided to fire Stanton and relieve one of the military commanders, General Philip Sheridan, who had dismissed the governor of Texas and installed a replacement with little popular support.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson was initially deterred by a strong objection from Grant, but on August 5, the President demanded Stanton's resignation; the secretary refused to quit with Congress out of session.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson then suspended him pending the next meeting of Congress as permitted under the Tenure of Office Act; Grant agreed to serve as temporary replacement while continuing to lead the Army.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Grant, under protest, followed Johnson's order transferring Sheridan and another of the district commanders, Daniel Sickles, who had angered Johnson by firmly following Congress's plan.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The President also issued a proclamation pardoning most Confederates, exempting those who held office under the Confederacy, or who had served in federal office before the war but had breached their oaths.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Although Republicans expressed anger with his actions, the 1867 elections generally went Democratic.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] No seats in Congress were directly elected in the polling, but the Democrats took control of the Ohio General Assembly, allowing them to defeat for reelection one of Johnson's strongest opponents, Senator Benjamin Wade.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Voters in Ohio, Connecticut, and Minnesota turned down propositions to grant African Americans the vote.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The adverse results momentarily put a stop to Republican calls to impeach Johnson, who was elated by the elections.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Nevertheless, once Congress met in November, the Judiciary Committee reversed itself and passed a resolution of impeachment against Johnson.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] After much debate about whether anything the President had done was a high crime or misdemeanor, the standard under the Constitution, the resolution was defeated by the House of Representatives on December 7, 1867, by a vote of 57 in favor to 108 opposed.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson notified Congress of Stanton's suspension and Grant's interim appointment.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In January 1868, the Senate disapproved of his action, and reinstated Stanton, contending the President had violated the Tenure of Office Act.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Grant stepped aside over Johnson's objection, causing a complete break between them.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson then dismissed Stanton and appointed Lorenzo Thomas to replace him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton refused to leave his office, and on February 24, 1868, the House impeached the President for intentionally violating the Tenure of Office Act, by a vote of 128 to 47.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The House subsequently adopted eleven articles of impeachment, for the most part alleging that he had violated the Tenure of Office Act, and had questioned the legitimacy of Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On March 5, 1868, the impeachment trial began in the Senate and lasted almost three months; Congressmen George S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Boutwell, Benjamin Butler and Thaddeus Stevens acted as managers for the House, or prosecutors, and William M.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Curtis and former Attorney General Stanbery were Johnson's counsel; Chief Justice Chase served as presiding judge.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The defense relied on the provision of the Tenure of Office Act that made it applicable only to appointees of the current administration.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Since Lincoln had appointed Stanton, the defense maintained Johnson had not violated the act, and also argued that the President had the right to test the constitutionality of an act of Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's counsel insisted that he make no appearance at the trial, nor publicly comment about the proceedings, and except for a pair of interviews in April, he complied.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson maneuvered to gain an acquittal; for example, he pledged to Iowa Senator James W.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Grimes that he would not interfere with Congress's Reconstruction efforts.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Grimes reported to a group of Moderates, many of whom voted for acquittal, that he believed the President would keep his word.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson also promised to install the respected John Schofield as War Secretary.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Ross received assurances that the new, Radical-influenced constitutions ratified in South Carolina and Arkansas would be transmitted to the Congress without delay, an action which would give him and other senators political cover to vote for acquittal.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] One reason senators were reluctant to remove the President was that his successor would have been Ohio Senator Wade, the president *pro tempore* of the Senate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Wade, a lame duck who left office in early 1869, was a Radical who supported such measures as women's suffrage, placing him beyond the pale politically in much of the nation.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Additionally, a President Wade was seen as an obstacle to Grant's ambitions.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] With the dealmaking, Johnson was confident of the result in advance of the verdict, and in the days leading up to the ballot, newspapers reported that Stevens and his Radicals had given up.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On May 16, the Senate voted on the 11th article of impeachment, accusing Johnson of firing Stanton in violation of the Tenure of Office of Act once the Senate had overturned his suspension.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Thirty-five senators voted "guilty" and 19 "not guilty", thus falling short by a single vote of the two-thirds majority required for conviction under the Constitution.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Ten Republicans—Senators Grimes, Ross, Trumbull, James Dixon, James Rood Doolittle, Daniel Sheldon Norton, William Pitt Fessenden, Joseph S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Van Winkle—voted to acquit the President.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] With Stevens bitterly disappointed at the result, the Senate then adjourned for the Republican National Convention; Grant was nominated for president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The Senate returned on May 26 and voted on the second and third articles, with identical 35–19 results.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Faced with those results, Johnson's opponents gave up and dismissed proceedings.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton "relinquished" his office on May 26, and the Senate subsequently confirmed Schofield.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When Johnson renominated Stanbery to return to his position as attorney general after his service as a defense manager, the Senate refused to confirm him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Allegations were made at the time and again later that bribery dictated the outcome of the trial.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Even when it was in progress, Representative Butler began an investigation, held contentious hearings, and issued a report, unendorsed by any other congressman.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Butler focused on a New York–based "Astor House Group", supposedly led by political boss and editor Thurlow Weed.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] This organization was said to have raised large sums of money from whiskey interests through Cincinnati lawyer Charles Woolley to bribe senators to acquit Johnson.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Butler went so far as to imprison Woolley in the Capitol building when he refused to answer questions, but failed to prove bribery.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Soon after taking office as president, Johnson reached an accord with Secretary of State William H.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward that there would be no change in foreign policy.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In practice, this meant that Seward would continue to run things as he had under Lincoln.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward and Lincoln had been rivals for the nomination in 1860; the victor hoped that Seward would succeed him as president in 1869.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] At the time of Johnson's accession, the French had intervened in Mexico, sending troops there.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] While many politicians had indulged in saber rattling over the Mexican matter, Seward preferred quiet diplomacy, warning the French through diplomatic channels that their presence in Mexico was unacceptable.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Although the President preferred a more aggressive approach, Seward persuaded him to follow his lead.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In April 1866, the French government informed Seward that its troops would be brought home in stages, to conclude by November 1867.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On August 14, 1866, Johnson and his cabinet gave a reception for Queen Emma of Hawaii who was returning to Hawaii after her trip to Britain and Europe.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward was an expansionist, and sought opportunities to gain territory for the United States.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] After the loss of the Crimean War in the 1850s, the Russian government saw its North American colony (today Alaska) as a financial liability, and feared losing control to Britain whose troops would easily swoop in and annex the territory from neighboring Canada in any future conflict.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Negotiations between Russia and the U.S. over the sale of Alaska were halted due to the outbreak of the Civil War, but after the U.S. victory in the war, talks resumed.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Russia instructed its minister in Washington, Baron Eduard de Stoeckl, to negotiate a sale.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] De Stoeckl did so deftly, getting Seward to raise his offer from $5 million (coincidentally, the minimum that Russia had instructed de Stoeckl to accept) to $7 million, and then getting $200,000 added by raising various objections.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] This sum of $7.2 million is equivalent to $166 million in present-day terms.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On March 30, 1867, de Stoeckl and Seward signed the treaty, working quickly as the Senate was about to adjourn.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson and Seward took the signed document to the President's Room in the Capitol, only to be told there was no time to deal with the matter before adjournment.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The President summoned the Senate into session to meet on April 1; that body approved the treaty, 37–2.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Emboldened by his success in Alaska, Seward sought acquisitions elsewhere.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] His only success was staking an American claim to uninhabited Wake Island in the Pacific, which would be officially claimed by the U.S. in 1898.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He came close with the Danish West Indies as Denmark agreed to sell and the local population approved the transfer in a plebiscite, but the Senate never voted on the treaty and it expired.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Another treaty that fared badly was the Johnson-Clarendon convention, negotiated in settlement of the *Alabama* Claims, for damages to American shipping from British-built Confederate raiders.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Negotiated by the United States Minister to Britain, former Maryland senator Reverdy Johnson, in late 1868, it was ignored by the Senate during the remainder of the President's term.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The treaty was rejected after he left office, and the Grant administration later negotiated considerably better terms from Britain.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson appointed nine Article III federal judges during his presidency, all to United States district courts; he did not appoint a justice to serve on the Supreme Court.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson appointed his Greeneville crony, Samuel Milligan, to the United States Court of Claims, where he served from 1868 until his death in 1874.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In June 1866, Johnson signed the Southern Homestead Act into law, believing that the legislation would assist poor whites.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Around 28,000 land claims were successfully patented, although few former slaves benefitted from the law, fraud was rampant, and much of the best land was off-limits, reserved for grants to veterans or railroads.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In June 1868, Johnson signed an eight-hour law passed by Congress that established an eight-hour workday for laborers and mechanics employed by the Federal Government.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Although Johnson told members of a Workingmen's party delegation in Baltimore that he could not directly commit himself to an eight-hour day, he nevertheless told the same delegation that he greatly favoured the "shortest number of hours consistent with the interests of all".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Selcer, however, the good intentions behind the law were "immediately frustrated" as wages were cut by 20%.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson sought nomination by the 1868 Democratic National Convention in New York in July 1868.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He remained very popular among Southern whites, and boosted that popularity by issuing, just before the convention, a pardon ending the possibility of criminal proceedings against any Confederate not already indicted, meaning that only Davis and a few others still might face trial.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On the first ballot, Johnson was second to former Ohio representative George H.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Pendleton, who had been his Democratic opponent for vice president in 1864.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's support was mostly from the South, and fell away as the ballots passed.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On the 22nd ballot, former New York governor Horatio Seymour was nominated, and the President received only four votes, all from Tennessee.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson sent Congress proposals for amendments to limit the president to a single six-year term and make the president and the Senate directly elected, and for term limits for judges.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When the President was slow to officially report ratifications of the Fourteenth Amendment by the new Southern legislatures, Congress passed a bill, again over his veto, requiring him to do so within ten days of receipt.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He still delayed as much as he could, but was required, in July 1868, to report the ratifications making the amendment part of the Constitution.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Seymour's operatives sought Johnson's support, but he long remained silent on the presidential campaign.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] It was not until October, with the vote already having taken place in some states, that he mentioned Seymour at all, and he never endorsed him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Nevertheless, Johnson regretted Grant's victory, in part because of their animus from the Stanton affair.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In his annual message to Congress in December, Johnson urged the repeal of the Tenure of Office Act and told legislators that had they admitted their Southern colleagues in 1865, all would have been well.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He celebrated his 60th birthday in late December with a party for several hundred children, though not including those of President-elect Grant, who did not allow his to go.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On Christmas Day 1868, Johnson issued a final amnesty, this one covering everyone, including Davis.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He also issued, in his final months in office, pardons for crimes, including one for Dr.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Samuel Mudd, controversially convicted of involvement in the Lincoln assassination (he had set Booth's broken leg) and imprisoned in Fort Jefferson on Florida's Dry Tortugas.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] On March 3, the President hosted a large public reception at the White House on his final full day in office.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Grant had made it known that he was unwilling to ride in the same carriage as Johnson, as was customary, and Johnson refused to go to the inauguration at all.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Despite an effort by Seward to prompt a change of mind, he spent the morning of March 4 finishing last-minute business, and then shortly after noon rode from the White House to the home of a friend.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] After leaving the presidency, Johnson remained for some weeks in Washington, then returned to Greeneville for the first time in eight years.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He was honored with large public celebrations along the way, especially in Tennessee, where cities hostile to him during the war hung out welcome banners.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He had arranged to purchase a large farm near Greeneville to live on after his presidency.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Some expected Johnson to run for Governor of Tennessee or for the Senate again, while others thought that he would become a railroad executive.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson found Greeneville boring, and his private life was embittered by the suicide of his son Robert in 1869.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Seeking vindication for himself, and revenge against his political enemies, he launched a Senate bid soon after returning home.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Tennessee had gone Republican, but court rulings restoring the vote to some whites and suppression of the African-American vote by the Ku Klux Klan led to a Democratic victory in the legislative elections in August 1869.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson was seen as a likely victor in the Senate election, although hated by Radical Republicans, and by some Democrats because of his wartime activities.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Although he was at one point within a single vote of victory in the legislature's balloting, the Republicans eventually elected Henry Cooper over Johnson, 54–51.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In 1872, there was a special election for an at-large congressional seat for Tennessee; Johnson initially sought the Democratic nomination, but when he saw that it would go to former Confederate general Benjamin F.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Cheatham, decided to run as an independent.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The former president was defeated, finishing third, but the split in the Democratic Party defeated Cheatham in favor of an old Johnson Unionist ally, Horace Maynard.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In 1873, Johnson contracted cholera during an epidemic but recovered; that year he lost about $73,000 (~$1.73 million in 2024) when the First National Bank of Washington went under, though he was eventually repaid much of the sum.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He began looking towards the next Senate election to take place in the legislature in early 1875.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson began to woo the farmers' Grange movement; with his Jeffersonian leanings, he easily gained their support.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He spoke throughout the state in his final campaign tour.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Few African Americans outside the large towns were now able to vote as Reconstruction faded in Tennessee, setting a pattern that would be repeated in the other Southern states; the white domination would last almost a century.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In the Tennessee legislative elections in August, the Democrats elected 92 legislators to the Republicans' eight, and Johnson went to Nashville for the legislative session.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] When the balloting for the Senate seat began on January 20, 1875, he led with 30 votes, but did not have the required majority as three former Confederate generals, one former colonel, and a former Democratic congressman split the vote with him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's opponents tried to agree on a single candidate who might gain majority support and defeat him, but failed, and he was elected on January 26 on the 54th ballot, with a margin of a single vote.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's comeback garnered national attention, with the *St.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Louis Republican* calling it "the most magnificent personal triumph which the history of American politics can show".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] At his swearing-in in the Senate on March 5, 1875, he was greeted with flowers, and sworn in alongside Hamlin (his predecessor as vice president) by incumbent Vice President Henry Wilson (who as senator had voted for Johnson's ouster).
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Many Republicans ignored Senator Johnson, though some, such as Ohio's John Sherman (who had voted for conviction), shook his hand.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson remains the only former president to serve in the Senate.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He spoke only once in the short session, on March 22 lambasting President Grant for his use of federal troops in support of Louisiana's Reconstruction government.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The former president asked, "How far off is military despotism?" and concluded his speech, "may God bless this people and God save the Constitution".
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson returned home after the special session concluded.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] In late July 1875, convinced some of his opponents were defaming him in the Ohio gubernatorial race, he decided to travel there to give speeches.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He began the trip on July 28, and broke the journey at his daughter Mary's farm near Elizabethton, where his daughter Martha was also staying.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] That evening he had a stroke, but refused medical treatment until the next day, when he did not improve and two doctors were sent for from Elizabethton.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He seemed to respond to their ministrations, but had another stroke on the evening of July 30, and died early the following morning at the age of 66.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] President Grant had the "painful duty" of announcing the death of the only surviving past president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Northern newspapers, in their obituaries, tended to focus on Johnson's loyalty during the war, while Southern ones paid tribute to his actions as president.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's funeral was held on August 3 in Greeneville.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] He was buried with his body wrapped in an American flag and a copy of the U.S.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] Constitution placed under his head, according to his wishes.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p02] The burial ground was dedicated as the Andrew Johnson National Cemetery in 1906, and with his home and tailor's shop, is part of the Andrew Johnson National Historic Site.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] According to Castel, "historians [of Johnson's presidency] have tended to concentrate to the exclusion of practically everything else upon his role in that titanic event [Reconstruction]." Through the remainder of the 19th century, there were few historical evaluations of Johnson and his presidency.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] Memoirs from Northerners who had dealt with him, such as former vice president Henry Wilson and Maine Senator James G.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] Blaine, depicted him as an obstinate boor who tried to favor the South in Reconstruction but was frustrated by Congress.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] Beale in his journal article about the historiography of Reconstruction, "Men of the postwar decades were more concerned with justifying their own position than they were with painstaking search for truth.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] The turn of the 20th century saw the first significant historical evaluations of Johnson.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] Rhodes ascribed Johnson's faults to his personal weaknesses, and blamed him for the problems of the postbellum South.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] Other early 20th-century historians, such as John Burgess, future president Woodrow Wilson, and William Dunning, concurred with Rhodes, believing Johnson flawed and politically inept but concluding that he had tried to carry out Lincoln's plans for the South in good faith.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] The resulting volumes, such as David Miller DeWitt's *The Impeachment and Trial of President Andrew Johnson* (1903), presented him far more favorably than they did those who had sought to oust him.
[src:buell-military-commission/andrew-johnson-p03] In James Schouler's 1913 *History of the Reconstruction Period*, the author accused Rhodes of being "quite unfair to Johnson", though agreeing that the former president had created many of his own problems through inept political moves.
